                    A flowchart illustrating the steps involved in a typical supervised learning process: data collection, data preprocessing, model training, model evaluation, and deployment.
                 </div><div class="page-break"></div><h2>Reinforcement Learning and Applications</h2>
               <p>Reinforcement learning (RL) is a distinct paradigm where an agent learns to interact with an environment by taking actions and receiving rewards or penalties. The goal is to learn a policy that maximizes cumulative rewards over time. RL algorithms, such as Q-learning and deep Q-networks (DQNs), are particularly well-suited for tasks involving sequential decision-making, such as game playing, robotics, and resource management. For instance, AlphaGo, a program that defeated a world champion Go player, was developed using reinforcement learning. In robotics, RL is used to train robots to perform complex tasks, such as walking, grasping objects, and navigating environments. The application of RL in autonomous driving is also gaining significant traction, enabling vehicles to learn optimal driving strategies in various scenarios. However, RL algorithms can be computationally expensive and require careful design of the reward function to ensure effective learning and avoid unintended consequences.</p><div class="diagram-placeholder">
